We recommended and the management agreed to:

Require the GSO-Designate to:

Prepare an updated list of all PPE items costing ₱ 50,000.00 and above;

Prepare/ update Property Cards for all PPE items reported as of December 31, 2022;

Prepare the Inventory and Inspection Report of Unserviceable Property (IIRUP) for all obsolete or unserviceable PPEs;

Reconcile property records with Accounting Unit; and

Submit to the Inventory Committee the updated list as basis in the preparation of working papers for the physical inventory taking activities.

Require the Municipal Accountant to:

Update/prepare PPELCs for all PPE items per Accounting records;

Ensure the updated PPELCs reconcile with the controlling PPE General Ledger accounts; and 

Reconcile property records with the Property Unit.

We recommended and the management agreed to:

Direct the Municipal Engineer to provide the Inventory Committee and the Municipal Accountant with a complete description and cost segregation of road components on road projects;

Require the Municipal Accountant and GSO-Designate to prepare, maintain and reconcile the Local Road Network Ledger Card and Property Card, respectively.

We recommended and Management agreed to:
Direct the Municipal Accountant to record advance payments for Real Property Tax (RPT) and Special Education Tax (SET) under the Deferred Real Property Tax and Deferred Special Education Fund Tax accounts respectively, and recognize income only when the revenue is earned;
Recognize the corresponding discounts granted for advance payments under the Discount on Advance Payments account and credit the account when the discount is applied;
Record all collections of fines and penalties arising from late payment of RPT and SET under the designated account Tax Revenue – Fines and Penalties – Property Taxes account; and
To avoid similar errors in the future, direct the Municipal Accountant to ensure proper segregation and classification of all components of real property tax collections, including current dues, advance payments, discounts, and penalties at the point of recording.

We recommended and Management agreed to:
Issue a new Executive Order (EO) or amend the existing EO to formally constitute an Inventory Committee with specific authority to conduct a full and comprehensive physical inventory of all PPE;
Ensure that future inventory activities are conducted collectively by the Inventory Committee and properly witnessed by the designated COA representative, as required under Sections 5.4 and 5.8 of COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020;
Require the Inventory Committee to prepare a detailed Physical Inventory Plan (PIP) and submit the duly approved PIP to the Audit Team at least ten (10) days before the commencement of inventory-taking activities;
Instruct the Inventory Committee to strictly adhere to the documentation requirements by utilizing the standard Inventory Count Form (ICF) daily for each PPE sub-major account group;
Ensure that all inventoried PPE items are tagged with property stickers compliant to the prescribed sequence to enhance traceability, accountability, and control over assets; and
Direct the GSO designate, in coordination with the accounting unit, to immediately undertake the reconciliation of the Property Cards (PCs) maintained by the property unit with the PPE Ledger Cards (PPELCs) to come up with reconciled balances of PPE accounts pursuant to Section 5.12 of COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020.

We recommended and Management agreed to:
Strictly comply with the documentary requirements prescribed under COA Circular No. 2012-001 dated June 14, 2012 for all repairs and maintenance transactions;
Implement a standard checklist of documentary requirements to be used as a control tool prior to the processing of payments for repairs and maintenance services;
Establish and maintain a repair history logbook for each government vehicle and equipment to monitor the frequency and cost of repairs, and to support decision-making on whether to continue repairing or consider the replacement of the asset; and
Assess the economic viability of repair transactions, ensuring that repair costs do not exceed 30% of the current market value of the equipment.

We recommended and Management agreed to:
Direct the Municipal Engineer to install the prescribed project signboards for every infrastructure project undertaken and ensure that they were regularly updated with relevant information;
Comply with all the transparency requirements of the 1987 Constitution as specified in Section 2 of COA Circular 2013-004, in all its infrastructure projects.

We recommended and the management agreed to:

Direct the Municipal Accountant to institute a sound Perpetual Inventory System pursuant to the Manual on NGAS for LGU’s to account for additions to and subtractions from Inventory;

Require the Municipal Accountant to record inventories upon receipt of procured supplies and materials. Recognize the corresponding expenses and only upon consumption or distribution based on submitted SSMI with certified copy of RIS. Maintain Ledger Cards and properly classify the assets and expenses accounts;

Direct the General Service Officer to maintain stock cards on the basis of Acceptance and Inspection Report and other documents like delivery receipt for inventories received. Further prepare the Report of Supplies and Materials Issued based on SSMI together with the original copy of the RIS on issued inventories. Submit to the Municipal Accountant for recording of expenses representing utilized/consumed inventories; and

Conduct periodic inventory of supplies and materials semestrally and reported in the Report of the Physical Count of Inventories (RPCI) not later than July 31 and January 31 of each year.

We recommended and the management agreed to:

Maximize the utilization of the 20% Development Fund and implement of the prioritized programs, projects activities as per Approved Annual Investment Plan (AIP). Closely coordinate among concerned officials in planning, execution and monitoring of project implementation;

Instruct the MPDC to look into the unimplemented development projects and identify causes of delay and come up with feasible doable specific solutions to address its effective implementation;

Direct the Municipal Engineer to execute the timely implementation of approved project. Likewise, conduct regular inspection, monitor, and evaluate project prosecution as to deliver the planned services in the AIP; and

Direct the Management to review the unspent balance of appropriations of CY 2022, in accordance with Section 322 of RA No. 7160.

We recommended and the management agreed to:

Direct the Municipal Accountant to:

Maintain the necessary perpetual inventory records including the Supplies Ledger Cards for each community/stock in accordance with Section114 of the NGAS for LGUs, Volume 1;

Record stock issuances only upon receipt of the SSMI with original copy of the RIS pursuant to Sections 121 of NGAS for LGUs Vol. 1;

Direct the Property Custodian-Designate to:

Maintain stock cards for supplies to track their receipt and disposal, and reconcile them with the accounting unit’s ledger cards;

Consolidate weekly the Requisition and Issue Slips (RIS) for which supplies and materials were issued using the Summary of Supplies and Materials Issued (SSMI) and submit it immediately, along with the RIS, to the Municipal Accountant for recording of the cost of the supplies and materials issued; and

Conduct a semestral physical count of inventory items by type, prepare the Report of the Physical Count of Inventories (RPCI), and submit the results to the Auditor concerned not later than July 31 and Jan 32 of each year for the first and second semesters respectively.

