We recommended and Management agreed to:

Direct the Bids and Awards committee (BAC) Secretariat together with the Accountant to immediately submit all the lacking supporting documents enumerated in Appendix J to enable the Audit Team to evaluate the procurements and strictly adhere to subsections of Section 9 of COA circular No. 2012-001;

Direct the BAC Secretariat to submit contract and its attached documents to the Office of the Auditor within five (5) days working days in adherence to the provisions of COA circular No. 2009-001 and Sections 9.1 of COA Circular No. 2012-001;

In view of the foregoing, we recommended and Management agreed to:

Instruct the property custodian to maintain an efficient property management by following the prescribed procedures in property recording and maintain accurate and complete property records;

Continuously reconcile the result of the physical count with the property and accounting records.

We recommended and Management agreed to:

Facilitate the processing of Certificate of Title of the untitled lots in order to establish absolute ownership and protect the legal interest of the LGU thereof pursuant to Section 148 of COA Circular No. 92-386;

Direct the Municipal Assessor to appraise the untitled lots to its current market value and provide the same to the Municipal Accountant for reference in recording in the book of accounts;
Direct the Municipal Accountant to record the subject property assets upon securing the Certificate of Title using the actual costs or appraised value if the former could not be determined; and

Direct the Municipal Treasurer to facilitate and supervise the proper payments of expenses for the land titling and to update and reconcile the inventory of property assets with the updated records of the Municipal Accountant.

We recommended and the management agreed to:

   a.  Instruct  the  Property  Custodian  to  observe  efficient  property management by following the prescribed procedures in  recording,  and maintaining accurate and complete PPE records;

   b. Direct the Property Custodian to  submit  an  updated  RPCPPE  as  of December 31, 2021;

   c. Reconstitute the Inventory Committee and prepare  Physical  Inventory Plan (PIP) specifying the specific  assignments,  the  cut-off  date, specifying the  schedule  dates  and  location  of  inventory  taking activities from start to the targeted date of completion as  provided in section 5.9 of COA Circular No. 2020-006;

   d. Direct  the  Municipal  Accountant  and  the  property  custodian  to reconcile and to adjust the difference between books of accounts and the property records respectively, as warranted; and

   e. Require the Inventory Committee and the Municipal Accountant to  look into and comply with the guidelines and procedures set forth  in the COA Circular No. 2020-006 to address issues and concerns on the non- existing and unserviceable assets.

We recommended and the management agreed to:

   a. Direct the Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) Secretariat  together  with the Accountant  to  immediately  submit  all  the  lacking  supporting documents enumerated in  Appendix  J  to  enable  the  Audit  Team  to evaluate the  procurements  and  strictly  adhere  to  subsections  of Section 9 of COA Circular No. 2012-001;


   b. Direct the BAC  Secretariat  to  submit  contracts  and  its  attached documents to the Office of the Auditor within five (5) working days in adherence to the provisions of COA Circular No. 2009-001  and  Section 9.1 of COA Circular No. 2012-001;


   c. Direct  the  Accountant  to  ensure  proper  and  complete  supporting documents are attached to all disbursement vouchers;


   d. Direct the Property Officer/Custodian to  ensure  the  filling  up  of complete data in the contracts, particularly the Purchase  Order  No., Mode of Procurement, Place and Date of Delivery, Delivery and Payment Term and the date when the supplier/contractor signify his  conformity to the terms and conditions of the POs/contract; and


   e. Direct the Acceptance and Inspection  Committee  to  indicate  in  the Acceptance and Inspection Report the actual  date  of  acceptance  and inspection of deliveries.

We recommended and the management agreed to:

   a. Require the Municipal Planning and Development Council to identify the specific program, projects and activities that partakes the nature  of an investments and capital expenditures in the 20% DF AIP pursuant  to Article 454 (d) of Rules and Regulations Implementing the LGC;

   b. Require the Municipal Accountant to  justify  why  contracts  for  the aforementioned PPAs were executed and disbursed without prior approval from the SB;

   c. Secure first approval or authorization from the Local Sanggunian prior to implementation of specific programs/projects/activities  under  the  20% DF funded out of lump sum appropriation pursuant to Article 4  (d)  of  the Rules and Regulation Implementing  the  Local  Government  Code (LGC) and Item 3.1.1 COA Circular No. 2012-001  as  clarified  in  COA Memorandum 2010-014 dated April 22, 2010; and

   d. Ensure that the 20% DF is  optimally  utilized  to  help  achieve  the desirable socio-economic development and environmental outcomes of the LGU”.

In view of the foregoing, we recommended that Management:
Facilitate the processing of Certificate of Title of the untitled lots in order to establish absolute ownership and protect the legal interest of the LGU thereof pursuant to Section 148 of COA Circular No. 92-386;
Direct the Municipal Assessor to appraise the untitled lots to its current market value and provide the same to the Municipal Accountant for reference in recording in the book of accounts;
Direct the Municipal Accountant to record the subject property assets upon securing the Certificate of Title using the actual costs or appraised value if the former could not be determined; and
Direct the Municipal Treasurer to facilitate and supervise the proper payments of expenses for the land titling and to update and reconcile the inventory of property assets with the updated records of the Municipal Accountant.

In view of the foregoing, we recommended that Management:
Direct the renewal of contract of lease in CY 2019 for qualified lessees and include stipulations therein for the compliance of their existing duties and responsibilities accumulated from CY 2015 to 2018;
See to it that contract of lease is executed between the LGU and the qualified new lessees before they are authorized to occupy the stall as compliance to Section 5A.07(a) of the Revised Municipal Revenue Code for strict enforcement of the duties and obligations of the parties;
Instruct the Public Market Committee to intensify efforts in the collection of overdue rentals and surcharges from delinquent market stall lessees as provided Sections 5A.04(a) of the same Revenue Code;
If possible, issue Statement of Accounts at least a month before the rent falls due to inform the lessees of their maturing obligation and ensure prompt payment of rentals;
Strictly impose the penalties set forth under and 5A.06(a)of the same Code;
Thoroughly implement other provisions of the Revenue Code intended for proper monitoring and control of the public market operation as stated under Section 5A.03 and Section 5A.05 of the Revenue Code on the imposition and recording of market entrance fees to promote efficiency; and
Formulate strategies and adequate control to regulate the entrance of transient vendors;
Earmark funds for the rehabilitation/renovation of the certain parts of the public market structure in accordance with the Implementing Rules and Regulations of the Code on the Sanitation of the Philippines for Markets and Abattoirs and regularly monitor the sanitation of the market as a whole in order to deliver quality and secured products and services in the public market.

In view of the foregoing, we recommended that Management:
Formulate the annual GAD Plan within the context of the mandate and overall plans and programs geared towards the protection of women’s and children rights against gender-based violence pursuant to Section 40 of RA No. 9262 and Section 4.1 Item C.2.4 of PCW-DBM-NEDA JMC No. 2013-001;
Develop comprehensive strategies and policies to provide and enable access to a full range of high quality health care services as assistance for gender-based violence victims towards healing, recovery and empowerment;
Establish linkages with NGAs that advocate for the protection of women and children’s rights and seek their participation for GAD activities; 
Expedite the development of a fully functional Crisis Center in order to provide temporary shelter and adequate services to the victims of violence; 
Evaluate the GAD PPAs implemented for prevention, intervention and reintegration in addressing gender related issues and concerns in terms of benefits delivered to target beneficiaries.

Submit accountant’s certification that proper accounting and/or liquidation of funds previously transferred to the PCL-Capiz Chapter has been complied with;
Submit a copy of the Memorandum of Agreement/Program of Work (POW) from the Implementing Agency showing detailed Plans and Specifications showing the objective/s and expected outcome/s duly approved by the Local Sanggunian;
Pictures and Inspection Report of implemented projects, if any; and
Require the Municipal Accountant to record the account “Due from” instead of “Donation” and submit the necessary liquidation reports relative thereto, for proper review and evaluation as to its regularity.

Observe the limitations on the types of programs/projects/activities that may be funded under the 20% Development Funds to conform the requirements laid down under DILG-DBM Joint Circular DILG-DBM No. 2011-1 dated April 13, 2011, amending DILG-DBM Joint Circular No. 1 dated September 20, 2005 and DILG Memorandum Circular No. 2010-138 dated December 2, 2010;
For disbursements enumerated in Table I, submit the following audit requirement for further review and evaluation, 1) Project Cost/Program of Work, and 2) Plans and Specifications stating, among others, the period of completion, length, width, date started and date completed; 3) Pictures before, during and after completion of the project and/or activities; 4) Inspection Report, Copy of the Statement of Work Accomplished/Progress Report/Accomplishment Report for 100% Accomplishment rendered by the Municipal Engineer; and 5) Copy of Certificate of Completion and Certificate of Acceptance (if any) for 100% Accomplishment.
For disbursements itemized in Annex E, 1) Classify the items paid and effect correcting entry to the appropriate Fund before closing the books of accounts, subject to availability of appropriations, and 2) Henceforth, strictly comply the provision of Section 4 of DILG-DBM Joint Circular excluding all expense items, such as: payment of electric bills, meals, overtime, honorarium, wages as well as supplies and materials which are not related to and/or not connected with the implementation of development projects, programs and activities in the preparation of Annual Investment Program of the succeeding years.

Submit justification pertinent to the award of eight (8) Purchase Orders (PO) containing items that exceeded the programmed amount per Program of Work (POW);
Include all programmed procurement during the year in the Annual Procurement Plan for consolidation prior to the conduct of bidding;
Consolidate all purchase requests prior to the conduct of bulk bidding and indicate specifications of each item in the APP to ascertain the lowest price possible;
Submit transactions for November and December 2015 specifically disbursements under the Water Program implemented by SBs Amponin and Reynaldo including the Office of the Local Chief Executive with a total budget cost of P2,736,300.00, for further evaluation;
Provide subsidiary ledger for each account with complete description and components of the asset;
Reconcile the listed assets/inventory vis-a-vis report and accounting record, and understand the description of the each account prior to recording in the subsidiary ledger to arrive at the correct classification;
Submit corresponding adjusting journal entries; and
Stop the practice of the Legislative Office in taking part in the implementation of programs, projects and activities specifically those PPAs under the 20% Development Program (Social Services and Access to Water Program) which is inherently lodged in executive branch to maintain the check and balance under the two branches.

Demand full liquidation of the outstanding cash advances of the concerned LGU Officials and Employees to avoid disallowance thereof;
Ensure proper monitoring of cash advances and implementation of existing rules and regulations including the withholding of salaries of accountable officers who failed to effect prompt liquidation thereof;
Ensure that cash on-hand plus receipts equals the original balance of petty cash fund duly supported with detail records to support all transactions prior to closing at the end of the year.

Ensure that all government transactions are recorded using proper account described in the COA Revised Chart of Accounts;
Observe the limitations on the types of programs/projects/activities that may be charged under the 20% Development and Calamity Funds to conform the requirements of the DILG-DBM Joint Circular DILG-DBM No. 2011-1 dated April 13, 2011, and RA 10121; and
Prepare and submit the necessary adjustments from account Other Maintenance and Operating Expenses to appropriate expense accounts for review and evaluation by this Office.
